# Instrumentation & Sensors — Water/Wastewater

## Instrumentation summary
| Parameter | Sensor Type | Typical Range | Calibration Consideration |
|---|---|---|---|
| pH | Glass electrode probe | 0-14 pH | 2-point calibration (buffer solutions, e.g. pH 4 & 7); electrode fouling/aging affects response time |
| Chlorine residual | Amperometric or colorimetric sensor | 0-10 mg/L | Regular reagent/membrane maintenance (colorimetric); zero/span calibration |
| Turbidity | Optical (nephelometric) sensor | 0-100+ NTU | Zero calibration with turbidity-free water; periodic lens cleaning |
| Flow | Magnetic flow meter or ultrasonic | Application-dependent | Verify zero flow reading; check for air entrainment affecting magmeter accuracy |
| Level | Ultrasonic or submersible pressure transmitter | Application-dependent | Verify against manual dip measurement; account for temperature effects on ultrasonic |
| Temperature | RTD or thermocouple | Application-dependent | Verify against calibrated reference thermometer |

## Calibration approach (general)
1. Verify sensor is clean and undamaged before calibration
2. Use certified reference standards (buffer solutions, calibration gas
   equivalent for liquid sensors, reference weights/instruments)
3. Perform zero and span calibration per manufacturer procedure
4. Document calibration date, reference values used, and as-found/as-left
   readings — same recordkeeping discipline used in gas detection
   calibration work
5. Set calibration frequency based on sensor drift history and criticality
   (similar logic to AMDEC-driven PM frequency in the mechanical project)

## Why this matters
Instrumentation drift is often invisible until it causes a process upset or
compliance issue. A technician who understands not just how to read a
transmitter but how and why to calibrate it — and who documents that
calibration — directly supports both process reliability and regulatory
compliance in a treatment facility.
